****Selenium WebDriver architecture*
🔄 How It Works (Flow)
You write a Selenium script
WebDriver converts it into a request
Request is sent via HTTP to the browser driver
Browser driver executes it in the browser
Response is sent back to your script

📊 Architecture Diagram (Conceptual)
Test Script
↓
WebDriver API (Language Binding)
↓
W3C WebDriver Protocol (HTTP/JSON)
↓
Browser Driver (ChromeDriver / GeckoDriver)
↓
Browser (Chrome / Firefox / Edge)

🧩 Key Components
1. Test Script (Client)
   Written in languages like Java, Python, C#, JavaScript
   Uses Selenium WebDriver APIs
2. WebDriver (Language Binding)
      Acts as a bridge between your test script and the browser driver
      Converts your code into JSON requests using the W3C WebDriver Protocol
3. WebDriver Protocol (W3C Standard)
      A standardized way for communication
      Uses HTTP requests (REST API)
Example:
POST /session
GET /url
4. Browser Driver
   Specific to each browser:
   Chrome → ChromeDriver
   Receives commands and interacts with the browser
5. Browser
   Executes the actual actions:
   Open URL
   Click buttons
   Fill forms

**********Selenium WebDriver Hierarchy (Java)*************
SearchContext (interface)
   ↑
WebDriver (interface)
   ↑
RemoteWebDriver (class)
   ↑
Browser-specific drivers
   ├── ChromeDriver
   ├── FirefoxDriver
   ├── EdgeDriver
   └── SafariDriver

🔹 1. SearchContext (Top-level interface)
Root of the hierarchy
Defines methods to find elements:
findElement()
findElements()

👉 Both WebDriver and WebElement inherit from this.
🔹 2. WebDriver (interface)
Main Selenium interface
Extends SearchContext
Key responsibilities:
Open/close browser
Navigate pages
Manage windows, timeouts, cookies
Important methods:
get()
navigate()
manage()
switchTo()
quit()

🔹 3. RemoteWebDriver (class)
Implements WebDriver
Core class that actually executes commands
Why it's important:
Used for Selenium Grid
Communicates with browser via JSON Wire Protocol / W3C protocol

🔹 4. Browser-specific Drivers

These extend RemoteWebDriver:

ChromeDriver
FirefoxDriver
EdgeDriver
SafariDriver

👉 Each driver knows how to control its specific browser.

🔹 5. WebElement (interface)
Represents elements on a webpage
Also extends SearchContext
Common methods:
click()
sendKeys()
getText()
getAttribute()

